embeddings.title: earthseed
embeddings.text:
earthseed
Historically, archives have been sites of erasure and capture, not sovereignty. Earthseed aims to reimagine an archive where stories are medicine. Earthseed is an intimate storytelling structure powered by interactive stars, pinecone architecture, and oral history interviews that speak on abortion, gender transitions, and care work. Inspired by sweat lodge ceremony and pinecones’ protective form, Earthseed is an experimental immersive archive that houses the intimate land/body stories shared between myself and longtime collaborator, Ximena Violante. 

Dre Jacome

embeddings.title: soft network
embeddings.text:
soft network
When you walk through a forest, you can feel the grass beneath your feet, smell the earth, hear and feel the wind weaving between the trees. When you are sitting at your desk to work, everything feels smooth. Every corner is rounded to precision, every metallic surface brushed to its maximum aesthetic potential. I smell nothing through the machine-purified air, there is no wind, and I hear only the taps and clicks of body hitting machine.
Anna Lin

embeddings.title: Thesis (title TBD)
embeddings.text:
Thesis (title TBD)
My thesis research investigates human-adjacent and non-human materials to flesh out my fascination with the corporeal. My guiding question is a selfish one: How are our bodies coerced without our knowledge? My neck tenses when I receive an unpleasant email. I run and rush, rather than enjoy my stroll, when late for another arbitrary start to the work day, saving perhaps a minute or two. In what ways are we affected by external  processes and systems? When do we see ourselves in non-human forms?
 

Taking these moments of disconnect from our bodies, I wonder how we might recognize ourselves outside of ourselves. How might objects, such as relics imbued with power or amulets worn for luck, have agency? How do we find, and/or impose, the distributed person in objects and materials, beyond the body-boundary? Activated by these questions, I began the process of trying to invert the traditional subject-object relationship through kinetic sculpture. 

Teresa L Wang

embeddings.title: Distance within Light
embeddings.text:
Distance within Light
My project intends to use light as a visual material to examine the distance between people within a confined recreational space
Tom Xia

embeddings.title: Jess's Thesis (untitled, TBD)
embeddings.text:
Jess's Thesis (untitled, TBD)
An LED installation that emphasizes audience presence and importance in the space. 
Jessica Shen

embeddings.title: interdepend.net
embeddings.text:
interdepend.net
interdepend.net is a website that is only accessible when a human generates enough power to start the server. The system creates a relationship between one side of the screen and the other, involving both the human power generator and any number of human browsers. The browsers will not be able to view the site without the generator, and the generator will not see the result of their labor without the browsers. The ensuing relationship is one of mutual dependency and reciprocity. It is the manifestation of man’s inability to get by alone. 
Jo Suk

embeddings.title: Jaxon Thesis '24
embeddings.text:
Jaxon Thesis '24 
This project explores the topic of ambient.

 Ambiance is happening in our lives at any given moment, in the past decade ambient media has become a new norm, from Lofi Hip-Hop girl to simply a fan in the room.  A lot of us need ambient background noise these days.

Rather than the issues of our attention span, this project explores the concept that ambient media/items serve companionship. How can ambient be served as companionship? 


The same companionship I seek in ambient media, I also find in my relationship with some of my objects. The tools I use as an extension of my body or other objects that support me emotionally through different days of my life. We have attachments to some of our objects.The value is not from the object itself, but the relationship we have with them. 

This project is an attempt at creating something that can bring some intimacy to people the same way ambient stuff and some of my objects brought me. 


Jaxon (Zidong) Wang

embeddings.title: Artedex
embeddings.text:
Artedex
How can we engage people to explore and learn from a city in fun and meaningful ways?

Embarking on a project to encourage exploration and learning in a city is driven by the recognition that, while we live in a diverse world, the rapid pace of modern life often keeps us from truly observing our surroundings. 

This initiative is rooted in the value of curiosity, a powerful force that transforms the ordinary into the extraordinary. It aims to reignite the sense of wonder in people, encouraging them to delve deeper into the stories, cultures, and histories that shape urban landscapes. In doing so, it creates opportunities for discovery and enriches our understanding of the places we live in.

This project is more than an exploration of urban spaces; it's a platform for connecting people. As individuals engage with their city, they also connect, turning the urban environment into a shared space of learning and experience. It bridges cultural and social divides, fostering a community of learners and explorers united by their shared journeys. Ultimately, this project celebrates the diversity of our world and the inquisitive human spirit, creating meaningful connections and a deeper appreciation of our cities and ourselves.
An-Kai Cheng

embeddings.title: Objective View of Contested Collection
embeddings.text:
Objective View of Contested Collection
An installation where viewers experience and imagine what it is like being a contested museum object in order to understand the issue of repatriation and restitution with a different framework. From purchase, conservation, display, to storage, viewers witness the way different meaning is attached at each stage and hopefully learn about the issue from their own perspective through the act of embodiment.
Queenie Huang

embeddings.title: Provenance
embeddings.text:
Provenance
Provenance is a tactile-audio narrative experience for one person in the dark. It begins in total darkness, with pieces the audience can touch and manipulate. As they move the pieces into place, the audience begins to hear spoken narration that tells them a story. There is a girl, and a mysterious artifact, and her quest to find the place where it belongs. As the audience explores and discover more of the story, the sensory world expands as well, adding more sound, more things to touch, and beginning to introduce light.
Alexandra Palocz

embeddings.title: Cytokinesis
embeddings.text:
Cytokinesis
At the genesis of human life, as meiosis unfolds, the delineation between individuals emerges, safeguarding the spectrum of diversity. Just as cells diverge from their parental origins, our distinctiveness crystallizes through the genesis of membranes. The membrane separates us into both subjects and objects. Through the membranes that tear us apart, we get closer to each other. Naming this project as Cytokinesis, which is the stage in meiosis where nuclear envelopes are formed while a cell’s cytoplasm divides to form two new cells, this project aims to cherish the membrane between the reciprocality developed in intimate relationships. With the intertwined call and response experience cultivated between 2 participants, Cytokinesis envisions a beautiful embodiment and a carnal adherence of both equilibrium and uniqueness. Built upon the premise of recreated soft, skin-like membranes with the encounter of hard metal bed frame that signifies an absent body,  the project entails a world of reciprocal affects and twist and turns that cumulates in relationships
Han Zhang

embeddings.title: TEst Thesis project
embeddings.text:
TEst Thesis project
test
Gracy Whelihan

embeddings.title: In and out of touch (working title)
embeddings.text:
In and out of touch (working title)
This project is part 1 of a series of explorations that started as an exploration of human’s sense of touch, and evolved into an ode to material and tactile interaction, as well as psychology, exploring the different ways we interact with physical objects depending on the material, the shape, the finishes, as well as the context they are placed in, and of course, the person interacting with them.
 
This part of the process is about the manufacturing of the objects, the engineering of the context to present them in, the interview with participants, and eventually making sense of the interaction I get out of them. This project will be continued linearly in terms of targeted exploration on context engineering and the human element of the interaction, as well as expanded laterally in terms of more diversity of materials and more ways of manufacturing.

Steve Sun

embeddings.title: Storytime
embeddings.text:
Storytime
Storytime is an interactive storytelling experience that uses toylike miniatures with projection mapping and on-screen animations to create a surreal environment to bring a digitally illustrated story into the physical world.
Anvay Kantak

embeddings.title: Burp World Online
embeddings.text:
Burp World Online
Burps have long been disrespected as an unserious form of sonic media. Labelled "vulgar" and "classless", the art of the belch is often responded to with vitriol and grimaces. 

For a large number of people burping is a way of life. Whether it be IBS or an addiction to Diet Cokes, those who know the truth of living with gas know that there's no holding it in. Be sneaky and pray for an inconspicuous release or disgust the people around you, it's a situation that gassy people can never win. That is until Burp World Online.

Burp World Online is a safe haven for burpers and belchers, where gas is celebrated and not criticised. 

I've found a gap in the market: there's no social media platform designed for the luscious sonic qualities of burps. Text based social media platforms like Twitter fall short, relying on the untrustworthy phoenetic interpretation of the burper. Video platforms like YouTube add too much bulk around the short and sweet burp. Platforms like Instagram and TikTok prioritise people that are hot, not the best burpers.

Burp World Online is made for the serious burper, using a fully sound-based user interface that respects the righteous burp. We've made it casual, spontaneous, and effortless to share your burp with the world.
Josh Zhong

embeddings.title: Social Protocols
embeddings.text:
Social Protocols
Through a series of experiments, Social Protocols examines how communication technology affects one’s ability to be vulnerable. In order to explore vulnerability, the project uses roleplaying, interactive web experiments, and re-enactment as methodologies to understand how medium and the message play hand in hand in shaping a conversation. This idea of embodied vulnerability can be seen through participants becoming a ‘performer’. Re-enactment offers the participant a chance to be vulnerable and reflect. Does the medium of communication change what we say and how we say it? 
Is it possible to construct the perfect conditions for technology to mediate vulnerability? In order to structure my creative research, the experiments investigate physical space, digital identity, physical vulnerability, affordances of media, physical contexts, access, and time. The experiments, ‘A-Home-Page’, ‘DMs in Public’, ‘Algorithms of Care’, ‘Pillow Talk’, invite participants to reach a point of discomfort in order to choose whether to be vulnerable.

Neeti Sivakumar

embeddings.title: Rebuttal Tracker
embeddings.text:
Rebuttal Tracker
Rebuttal Tracker is a tool for real-time data exploration and for mapping routes around public surveillance infrastructure. By inserting a person's live location within a map of surveillance cameras, they are able to more clearly visualize the density & frequency of which they may intersect with the lenses of these cameras. The act of explicitly knowing & sensing these devices which may otherwise remain hidden & forgotten bring to light the issues of transparency & consent that the vast implementation of these cameras in public space raise. By engaging with this infrastructure knowingly while acting out day-to-day life and motion, folks who engage with this project are refuting the claim that they require such surveillance as they are not deserving of accusal or search based on their action - they offer a rebuttal this infrastructure evidence that watches them & asserts otherwise. Additionally, the ability to map out alternative routes to one's planned ventures that exceed the bounds of this video surveillance (or be faced with the fact that there is no alternate route), the vastness of these systems is re-enforced and the lack of ability to opt-out of such programs crystalized.
Sam Hafferty

embeddings.title: I'm tired of cleaning your mess
embeddings.text:
I'm tired of cleaning your mess
Whether it's picking up a mirror toppled over by the roomba, or yanking a charging cord off a moving roomba, the artist is inspired by her daily struggle of cleaning up after failed automation. This performance explores the juxtaposition of when technology works wonders versus when it inevitably fails, and how humans have to intervene after such failures. Using a robotic arm, the artist highlights three different ways of how machines fail: machines realize their failures and awaits for further assistance, machines realize their failures and try to fix their own mistakes, and machines don't realize their failures and continue to function in dysfunctional manners. In creating this performance, the artist invites audiences to reflect on the increasingly omnipresent automation in our daily lives.
Michelle Mong Qi Wu

embeddings.text:
there’s nothing here worth dying for.

Briana Jones

embeddings.title: Community Canvas
embeddings.text:
Community Canvas
Community Canvas is a web-based platform built to facilitate the first (idea generation) and second (project development) steps of the participatory budgeting (PB) process as implemented in NYC, particularly in the context of renovation, renewal, and repurposing of public spaces. Community Canvas invites users, i.e., community members, to express their ideas virtually using handheld devices to arrange accurate-to-scale 3D models in space. The Brennan Center for Justice identifies energetic and thoughtful outreach, clarity on what PB can and can't do, and giving residents actual control as among the key takeaways from interviews with citizens about the factors leading to PB's success. On the user end, Community Canvas presents an exciting new way to articulate ideas for how public space can be used, covering for the limitations of existing text- or map-based submissions. On the local government side, it provides an innovative means of outreach, through which representatives can not only keep constituents informed of the PB process through notifications, updates, and other important information about budget and PB limitations through the app interface, but also engage them through presenting a channel of direct communication with their representatives.
Mashi Zaman

embeddings.title: Light: AI companion powered by therapy method
embeddings.text:
Light: AI companion powered by therapy method
Light is an AI-driven voice chat App designed to serve as a companion who can help its users address their mental concerns through affordable and therapeutic solutions.

Inspired by Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) principles, the product leverages voice as its primary mode of interaction, guiding users through constructive sessions tailored to address their troubles and concerns. The experience positions users in a therapeutic environment in which they would gradually unpack their thoughts and reflect on their concerns by talking to the AI companion. It also aims to promote long-term growth by providing session summaries at the end of each session and using the history of the previous sessions to assist future conversations. The project aims to provide users with an educational tool to help them explore ways to self-reflect on their mental challenges and get a taste of talking therapy prior to necessitating professional medical intervention.

Light explores the potential of AI chatbots taking the roles of emotional companions in our lives. The project investigated the solutions for safeguarding user data privacy while effectively offering emotional support to the users.

Austen Li

embeddings.title: Interactive Diorama
embeddings.text:
Interactive Diorama
The project is designed as an interactive diorama game that functions similarly to a board game. Players engage with the game by following audio instructions and visual cues to navigate and complete each level sequentially. This leveled structure ensures that players must clear one area before progressing to the next. The game concludes after players successfully complete the final level, providing a structured and immersive gameplay experience.
Chenghong Tang

embeddings.title: The Echoes Unheard
embeddings.text:
The Echoes Unheard
“The Echoes Unheard” is a web-based interactive storytelling experience. It invites the audience into a virtual landscape crafted by the artist, guiding them through the whispered melodies created in marginalized dialects. This journey intertwines the poetic beauty hidden in these languages with personal echoes from the artist that pulse with the music. Through engaging with this digital landscape, the audience gains a deeper appreciation for the nuanced cultural narratives and the profound personal stories that resonate within the overlooked poetic essence of these languages. The experience culminates in an invitation for the audience to share a song of personal significance, rewarding them with a customized digital vinyl image as a souvenir of their journey.
Lily Yu

embeddings.title: Untitled
embeddings.text:
Untitled
In this intimate theatrical experience, you meet college student Alice who has volunteered for a Big Tech experiment - they have developed a chip they can implant in your brain that lets you then control the technology around you with your thoughts. The Big Tech Company is monitoring Alice’s chip’s functionality as it comes online by having her navigate a simple video game demo first with a game controller, and then with her thoughts. Throughout the whole encounter, you are in conversation with her about personal technology - do you control your tech or does your tech control you?

This is the first chapter in my decentralized, science fiction narrative experience, which at this time also includes a short Virtual Reality game following the same character.
Zoe Margolis

embeddings.title: I'll Meet You at the Rainbow Bridge
embeddings.text:
I'll Meet You at the Rainbow Bridge
"I'll Meet You at the Rainbow Bridge" aspires to guide the solitary path of pet loss toward a shared journey of remembrance and healing. Born from a personal story of loss, this virtual sanctuary invites individuals to celebrate the lives of their beloved pets within a serene world. By merging the tangible act of memorialization with the realms of digital space, this project envisions a world where the grief of pet loss is shared, understood, and hopefully, a little easier to bear. 
Levitia Patricia

embeddings.title: TravARlog
embeddings.text:
TravARlog
IOS App pair with custom design postcard that seamlessly blend traditional interactions with modern technologies, creating a novel and deeply personal experience in the digital age. Grounded in the belief that the fusion of physical and digital realms has the potential to redefine our interaction with memories. Recognizing the contemporary landscape of advanced technology, my exploration focuses on the innovative applications of Extended Reality. Motivated by a desire to revive the joy of exchange diaries. Exchange diaries, also known as "kōkan nikki" in Japanese, were a popular trend in the 1990s in Japan. Friends would share a notebook and take turns writing their thoughts, comments, or experiences. It is a nostalgic and personal way to connect and share moments with each other.
Wendy Ho

embeddings.title: Boundless
embeddings.text:
Boundless
Boundless is an ongoing work combining high fashion aesthetics with hardware and wearable technology. The goal of this project is to create wearable, programmable circuit boards that also have a strong aesthetic sense, and utilize jewelry-making and craft techniques to solve electrical engineering problems. This series includes a large-scale chainmail-style PCB board dress, an LED pulsing PCB necklace, and a harness piece that accesses data via wifi to display planetary positions through LEDs. This project began as me seeking to create an LED grid with flexibility coming from linking together the LEDs in the manner of chainmail or jewelry, as opposed to mounting them on a flexible plastic or fabric surface. As the project evolved, I began incorporating PCB design as a surface to mount the LEDs on, and eventually, the PCBs as an essential  decorative part of the piece themselves. I really came to aesthetically appreciate the copper finish of DIY PCBs, which literally incorporates precious metals into the piece, as well as being functional for designing circuit boards. 
Marrying fashion aesthetics and jewelry-making techniques with elements more commonly associated with engineering is very important to me and this work. Boundless demonstrates how it's possible to solve technological and engineering problems with techniques dismissed as crafty or feminine, just as much as it’s possible to solve aesthetic and fashion problems with electrical elements.
Kay Wasil

embeddings.title: Nardin
embeddings.text:
Nardin
This project explores the possibility of using real-time changes in musical audio effects to generate music. This idea started as a challenge I faced when doing an assignment to link one slider to many musical parameters of an instrument, building on top of that I made this hardware synth/audio effects unit that has one slider to control many parameters.
Nima Niazi

embeddings.title: A Synthesis of Everything I Care About
embeddings.text:
A Synthesis of Everything I Care About
I didn’t grow up religious but found my way into a church walking home from a visit with my sister. I was about 13. I remember being struck by the vastness of the incredible welcoming space; the stillness, the quiet, the quality of light emphasizing the beauty of the iconography - it filled me with awe and it spoke to me in a language that only my heart could decipher. Soon I was growing accustomed to the Christian Orthodox way of life. I remember my first Easter night service: tears streaming down my face and my heart jolting with joy for no apparent reason other than that of being alive. The only word that comes close to describing that experience is LOVE. I felt so close and connected to everyone around me even if they were strangers. It was during those years that I came across the passage in the 1 Corinthians 13: “Love is patient, love is kind. It does not envy, it does not boast, it is not proud. It is not rude, it is not self-seeking, it is not easily angered, it keeps no record of wrongs. Love does not delight in evil but rejoices with the truth. It always protects, always trusts, always hopes, always perseveres. Love never fails.” I thought, what an ideal to live up to! Thesis delves deeper into this mystery. “What is it that we risk by making love our duty?” – is the question driving this research and it is explored through the concept of the mask that hold back from love, the sacrifice  – to overcome ourselves to meet the other, and the gift – which in the final analysis shows that even in the face of any perceived risk, love practiced as choice or duty, is that which blesses you.
Andriana Mereuta

embeddings.title: PCB (Printed Comic Boards)
embeddings.text:
PCB (Printed Comic Boards)
Novices learning about electronics for the first time often face difficulties due to the abstract nature of the subject. Through anthropomorphism, the humanization of non-human entities. By attaching human qualities to electronic components. This leverages the cognitive bias to understand qualities and behaviors through metaphorical analogies to the human experience. Through a creatively designed comic book printed on the silkscreen of a Printed Circuit Board (PCB), electronic components are reimagined as characters with distinct personalities, quirks, and societal roles. This serves as both a visual guide and a functional example of the electronics at play, bridging the gap between theoretical knowledge and practical understanding.
Vera Liqian Zhong

1642
This project, named 1642, brings music to Rembrandt's painting, The Night Watch. The painting was done in 1642 in Amsterdam, and it is one of the most famous and important paintings in Western art history. The project commences by breaking the painting into multiple layers. The bottom layer consists of the architecture in the background, followed by layers representing the characters from behind to front. Each person is digitally represented and painted. Throughout the painting of the background and layers, as well as the inclusion of intricate details, sound is being played simultaneously to provide audiences with a more immersive experience. The selected sounds are sourced from classical music in the Baroque era. the same era as the painting was created.The project necessitates extensive research into daily life in Amsterdam during the mid-17th century. An in-depth exploration of clothing and attire belonging to different social classes and occupations of that period is crucial, still, as the blocked figures in the back layers are also depicted.Ultimately, all 31 characters plus a dog allocate their specific spot, time, music, and unique representation. A script is written to organize the project, detailing the sequence of each layer, ensuring a harmonious fusion of visuals and sounds. The animation is projected at a 1:1 scale of the painting, measuring at 11' 11" x 14' 4". It is hoped that this immersive experience brings the audience a grander, theatrical, and dramatic encounter within the context of the combination of the visual splendor of Rembrandt in Dutch Golden Age and the timeless allure of classical music. 
Long L

▯
In urban landscapes, towering structures and adorned windows weave a tangible web across the spaces that people inhabit, resembling a complex network. Screens, in their innate resemblance to windows, share a rectangular form, acting as frames or portals that bridge two or more realms. As a generation that grew up in cities and witnessed the development of the internet, I instinctively harbor suspicions about these connections. Because, at some point, whether in physical reality or digital reality, I constantly shift from one rectangular space to another. It's as if existence itself has been arranged and compartmentalized into boxes. It seems like we are online anytime, anywhere, and offline becomes an impossibility. I’m interested in the shifting and the overlapping between different boxes.
Yizhi Liu

embeddings.title: Tangible Values
embeddings.text:
Tangible Values
I am an over-thinker, but for the most part, it is because I like thinking. I wanted to use this project to share a part of what I like and to create a space for you to think about various things as well. This project is an interactive website with 3D elements that showcase 4 thought experiments and allow for people to act upon the decision presented in each thought experiment prompt.
Traveling past the introductory foyer, you will come across an onboarding experience demonstrated through the Dictator Game. Upon completion, I invite you to freely navigate to areas presenting the Volunteer Dilemma, Exchange Game, and Trust Game. In each area, a floating diamond will be your point of contact, revealing the area’s respective thought experiment prompt and relaying instructions on completing the corresponding interactive component.
The goal of this project is to make the experience of thought experiments more engaging by improving the tangibility of values upheld whilst thinking through the various scenarios. The implementations I have made are centered around adding interactivity to conventionally written text, using technology to showcase this experience visually in a digital realm and representing decisions made with actions taken. In making values more tangible, I hope to inspire reflection on what people care about and possible reasons behind their actions.
Athena Zhou

embeddings.title: Do Nothing Compaany
embeddings.text:
Do Nothing Compaany

After a few years of exploring the theme of working culture, I initiated the project Do Nothing Company in 2024 as my thesis project. It is a project centered around a conceptual company that hires people to practice doing nothing. Currently, I am building it by using the Unreal Engine. In the Do Nothing Company’s virtual world, all the characters only play idle animations and remain inactive. Additionally, I would collaborate with a composer to create a piece of sound by exclusively using whistle sounds, a universal expression of joy or cheerfulness.
In 2024, where burnout is all too common, I wish to share the message to encourage people to embrace the power of doing nothing.

Lisha Nie

embeddings.title: Symbiosis
embeddings.text:
Symbiosis
Symbiosis is an exploration of interaction within generative arts. In the current landscape of generative art, we often see complex computative generated visuals but often have little or no means to interact with them or further understand them. Symbiosis aims to allow audiences to play with generative systems, observe and understand behaviors and patterns, and use that knowledge to create visuals unique to themselves. By using a generative design that mimics natural movement and concepts from nature, Symbiosis invites audiences to understand the visuals as if they were observing life in nature.

Symbiosis exists in two forms. As a web game and as an installation, by exploring different interactive mediums for the generative system I aim to use interactivity to recontextualize the artwork as a whole. Through different mediums and technologies, Symbiosis aims to explore the influence of technological mediums on our understanding of the content being presented to us.
Daniel Wai

embeddings.title: Silent Whisper
embeddings.text:
Silent Whisper
“Silent Whisper” is inspired by my trip to Iceland. When I was standing among glaciers, in the middle of nowhere, I saw that time was frozen within it. The trail of wind, illustrated by volcanic ash, was compressed into the glacier layer by layer chronologically. With the absence of human societies, people were battered by the howling wind and snow, swaying like wild grass, which made me suddenly realize how small individuals are. Through interactive visual effects, physical installations, and multi-sensory experience, “Silent Whispers” reflects the relationship between people and invisible forces in their societies, which are so taken for granted that people mostly don’t realize they exist.

Junru Chen

embeddings.title: Beyond
embeddings.text:
Beyond
"Beyond" is a video installation exploring the presence of the unseen photographer. It reflects the artist's struggle with feeling absent in their own captured memories. Viewers are invited to reconsider the significance of those behind the camera and reflect on their relationship with memory and presence.
Zeynep Elif Ergin

embeddings.title: null
embeddings.text:
null
"null" explores the perennial human yearning for immortality. Throughout various mythologies, it is evident that humans have contemplated the notion of immortality since ancient times. This pursuit continues today, with many wealthy individuals investing substantial amounts of money in immortality tech, making immortality startups a trending phenomenon. I, too, have been inescapably drawn to ponder over the concept of death.

Yuval Noah Harari, in his writings, posits that humanity's future direction is towards 'immortality.' He suggests that through cyborg technology, biotechnology, and smart drugs, humans are set to transform themselves, aiming for states of 'non-death' or becoming 'superhuman.' As immortality becomes increasingly tangible, my desire is to underscore the distortion and eeriness associated with it.

To this end, as an artistic representation of immortality's distortions, I will preserve my own DNA within the blockchain. The inherent nature of blockchain-recorded data, which becomes immutable and indestructible, serves this purpose.

By eternally storing my DNA on the blockchain, I aim to express 'digital immortality.' This method seeks to explore the possibility of continuing to 'exist' in some form even after death.
Riho Hagi

embeddings.title: It's never me
embeddings.text:
It's never me
My thesis work is a movement-based investigation that seeks new ways of processing information to lessen the internal and external burden of our existence. It harnesses the power of collective thinking and collaboration through outsourcing sentiment – i.e., engaging the public to interpret the intentions and understand the emotional state of the subject. This investigation is conducted through digital self-manifestation and creation of a fully autonomous avatar, Notame.
 
This investigation will be presented in two forms: a physical artifact and a performance.

Maryia Markhvida

An Expression of Flow

embeddings.title: Gadgets to Live By
embeddings.text:
Gadgets to Live By
"Gadgets to Live By" is a project born from the intersection of technology, personal experience, and the quest for pursuing mental well-being. This collection of gadgets emerges as a deliberate counter to the relentless pace of digital consumption and the often overlooked emotional landscapes navigated in our daily lives. Central to the project are two gadgets: "Haiku News" and "Decision Maker," each designed with the purpose of integrating technology into our lives in a way that promotes reflection and mental health.

"Haiku News" reimagines the way we consume news by transforming anxiety-inducing headlines into tranquil haiku poetry, displayed on an e-paper screen. This gadget offers a meditative pause from the bombardment of traditional news, providing a reflective space that encourages contemplation and emotional distance from the explicit and subjective realities portrayed in the media. "Haiku News" addresses the impact of information overload on our mental health, offering an alternative that soothes rather than stimulates anxiety.

The "Decision Maker" gadget responds to the indecisiveness that can often accompany mental health struggles. Combining the whimsy of a magic eight ball with the excitement of a slot machine, it not only entertains but also provokes thoughtfulness for the user, challenging them to reflect on the questions they pose and assist with the decisions they face in everyday life.

Designed, 3D printed, and assembled with care, these gadgets are not just tools but companions in the journey of life, offering insights and interventions in moments of need. "Gadgets to Live By" stands as a testament to the power of thoughtful design in creating gadgets that doesn't just occupy space in our lives but enriches it, fostering well-being, reflection, and a deeper engagement with the world around us.
Hank Hsu

embeddings.title: Programmable Cassette
embeddings.text:
Programmable Cassette
When was the last time you used a Walkman? Cassette tapes played an important role in my childhood and I wanted to revive the technology with the introduction of more accessible programming technology.
Xiaotian Zhang

embeddings.title: The Great Conjuring
embeddings.text:
The Great Conjuring
Stepping barefoot onto a bed of earth in a darkened room, the hushed hum of an ambient soundscape washes over you and a light in the center invites you. An open umbrella becomes a portal, its surface alive with ever-evolving, AI-generated visuals. 

This art piece is part of a larger research into the intrinsec relations between magic, technology, humans and nature. Magic is a constant presence in our lives as humanity, helping us understand the world and connect with it. It’s meaning changed extensively over time and I now try to understand: What is magic? What defines a magic experience? Why do we talk about technology in terms of “magic”? What are the mechanisms of power incited by this vocabulary?

This multisensory immersive installation invites interactors to practice a state of presence, creativity and contemplation state of mind to reimagine our connections with nature, technologies, with our ways of engaging with the world around us and, ultimately, with this mysterious and broad concept of magic.
This piece aims to bridge Artificial intelligence, the lastest "magic"-evoking trend of technology, with the most primitive awe-inspiring "magic" of nature itself with its own technologies that inspired us as humanity.
Micaelle Lages

embeddings.title: If "YOU" do manipulate, then I'm innocent.
embeddings.text:
If "YOU" do manipulate, then I'm innocent.
I suffered great changes in my life over the past few years. Having lost much that was important to me, I began to contemplate life introspectively. I'm not religious, and I don't have something to pray for every time I feel lost and stuck. Sometimes I'm just genuinely curious, is there truly something called fate? Then, when I'm suffering, it doesn't necessarily mean I did something wrong. 'Fate' sometimes can be a vent or excuse for me to escape. For my thesis, I decided to delve deeper into the concept of 'Fate'. This website showcases all those deep explorations.

I interviewed people and transformed their thoughts about 'Fate' into an interactive website to showcase different opinions on this topic.
Keyi Fu

embeddings.title: Spectral Signatures
embeddings.text:
Spectral Signatures
For centuries, signatures have served as a symbolic extension of our identity, appearing on contracts, artwork, and personal documents. Signatures have served as more than just a means of authentication; they are reflections of our identities, beliefs, and creativity.

Imagine a signature evolving beyond its static form, becoming an animated representation of the individual behind it. This project delves into the concept of signatures embodying facets of our personality, transforming them into living organisms that reflect individual character traits.

By infusing signatures with subtle animations and distinct visual styles, each signature takes on a personality and movement, mirroring the diversity and nuances of the individuals they represent. This exploration seeks to redefine how we perceive signatures, turning them into dynamic expressions of identity rather than static marks on paper.

Furthermore, this endeavor seeks to challenge conventional notions of signatures as mere legal marks, instead reimagining them as vibrant expressions of identity and self-expression. It invites viewers to ponder the deeper connections between identity, creativity, and the visual representation of one's persona.

Ultimately, this project aims to spark conversations about the multifaceted nature of human identity and the endless possibilities of artistic expression in the digital age.
Jane Cheng

embeddings.title: null: there is always room (for not making a choice)
embeddings.text:
null: there is always room (for not making a choice)
Null: There is always room (for not making a choice) is a terminal simulation of web art where the audience is flooded with a series of life situation questions with and without automatic answers of ‘null.’

The work aims to symbolize the forgiving nature and inclusivity inherent in 'null,' conveying the message that it is perfectly acceptable to refrain from making a choice when faced with life struggles.
Yu-Ying Lee

embeddings.title: Rhythms of Time: An Immersive VR Meditation Journey
embeddings.text:
Rhythms of Time: An Immersive VR Meditation Journey
This project use VR to create an immersive meditation experience aimed to alleviate the anxiety caused by the fast-paced nature of contemporary life. It introduces a approach to relaxation and mindfulness by simulating diverse life rhythms through various patterns of sphere movements, accompanied by voiceover and music. This  experience is designed to help users adjust their breathing, relax their body and mind, and reshape their perception of time.

In this meditation experience, I will gradually guide users through six motion modes, using them to help users into a meditative state where they can adjust their mindset in the  changing rhythms.

1. **Concentric Circles Movement**: Represents the steady flow of time, encouraging deep inner peace and focus.
2. **Expansion and Contraction**: Emulates the rhythm of breathing, promoting relaxation and balance between tension and ease. 
3. **Offset Pendulum**: Reflects life's inevitable fluctuations, teaching users to find stability amidst changes. 
4. **Random Walk**: Encourages the acceptance of uncertainty, fostering a calm approach to life's unpredictability.  
5. **Intersecting Trajectories**: Demonstrates the search for order within chaos, guiding users to find harmony in complexity.
6. **Spiral Ascension**: Symbolizes personal growth, encouraging users to contemplate their development path.

By guiding users through these varied rhythms, the VR meditation experience aims to provide a sanctuary from the stresses of modern life, offering a path to inner tranquility and a redefined sense of time. This immersive journey not only seeks to reduce anxiety but also to enrich users' lives with greater mindfulness and a balanced perspective on life's ever-changing pace.
Xiaoran Chen

embeddings.title: Pharmi (WIP)
embeddings.text:
Pharmi (WIP)
We have a loneliness and mental health epidemic that affects all age groups in the US, with people less likely to be active in a community and less likely to value relationships than generations before them. Today, 20-40% of Americans suffer from a mental health disorder, according to the National Institute of Mental Health, and according to the U.S. Surgeon General, young people aged 15-24 have 70% less social interaction with their friends than they did 20 years ago. It's no wonder people are turning to robots like PARO, MyRealBaby, and Replika more and more for emotional connection.

Since the pandemic closures, therapy and psychiatry have become even larger booming businesses. Combine that with our government already being in bed with Big Pharma and Big Tech, we have a very interesting set of incentives behind future products of Health Tech.

What might the future of Human-Robot Interaction look like? With this gaping need for companionship and desire for emotional support, what type of companionship robot might we design? Generative AI is already passing bar and medical exams, but should we trust them to be at the steering wheel of medical decisions? What perverse incentives might Health Tech have in producing companionship robots and is this a good or bad thing for society?

In an effort to explore these questions through parody, I present a companionship robot that is made by and approved by Big Tech and Big Pharma*. One that will always lend an open ear and is designed to be your closest friend and is trained on medical data that aims to address the loneliness and mental health epidemic, with the ability to diagnose and treat its patients. But for whose benefit? The patient or the corporations?

*Not actually approved by anyone in either of these fields.

Karina Chow

embeddings.title: Identity in Transit: The Journey of an Immigrant
embeddings.text:
Identity in Transit: The Journey of an Immigrant
The immigrant experience in New York is not only one of opportunity, but also one marked by unexpectedness, frustrations, disappointments, and challenges in making meaningful connections and fully assimilating. This immersive installation hopes to provide a platform for the multifaceted immigrant experience, encapsulating both the transient struggles and enduring triumphs. Through intimate interviews with nine individuals, it endeavours to capture their memories and their journey to evoke and simulate the feelings of being an outsider.

Dipika Titus

embeddings.title: Say HeeHee
embeddings.text:
Say HeeHee
Say HeeHee is a web-based virtual pet game experience. Here, players get their own exclusive pets - the Smile Pets, and help the pets grow and level up through smiling. The pets will also follow users to any websites they are on. This game aims to unwind, accompany, and provide positive feelings to people. Based on the Facial Feedback Theory, which posits that facial expressions can influence a person's emotional experiences (i.e., smiling can make someone feel happier), this game integrates various interactive features aimed at enhancing players' emotional well-being.
Elodie Liu

embeddings.title: Surveillance Synthesis
embeddings.text:
Surveillance Synthesis
This installation piece layers and composes footage from surveillance footage from publicly accessible sources and the camera, which captures the audience, creating a half-real digital world. The work is a commentary on the potential impact of technology on our personal privacy and safety, as well as the balance between security measures and individual freedoms.
Yi-Chun Lan

embeddings.title: Head Break
embeddings.text:
Head Break
In "Head Break," users interact with different objects in virtual reality, emphasizing seamless hand-tracking implementation to provide an accessible entry into virtual reality. Motivated by a passion for VR and wanting to introduce someone to VR, my grandma being my initial reason, this project merges intuitive hand-tracking with easy to take in visuals. Influenced by the Hedonomoic VR principles, the aim is to create a welcoming VR environment for newcomers. 
Sam De Armas

embeddings.title: Compa
embeddings.text:
Compa
Compa is the 21st-century version of a pen pal correspondence, designed for the digital age. It uses multimedia to foster meaningful connections between users, aiming to alleviate feelings of loneliness and stress while forming healthy friendship connections.

The app's core functionality revolves around users completing small daily tasks over a 30-day period. These tasks are designed to be engaging and creative, allowing users to express themselves in various ways. Upon completing each task, users share their results anonymously with the Compa community, and in return, they receive task results from other users. The anonymous nature of the interactions allows users to be more open and authentic, without the pressure or expectations that can sometimes accompany traditional social media platforms.

Alfonssette Joselin Medina Bonilla

embeddings.title: Temporary Spaces
embeddings.text:
Temporary Spaces
As a designer, I prioritize creating structured and efficient environments. Yet, there's value in elements that transcend these boundaries. The urgent need for temporary spaces, bypassing the wait for revised design systems, parallels patching designed systems. The allure of these spaces lies not only in their immediacy but also in their profound impact on the urban landscape(or any designed systems). They serve as unexpected interjections, challenging the established norms of systematic design. 

These spaces captivate me, prompting an exploration of them across locations and their role in establishing spatial justice in contemporary urban life. Over years, my self-initiated projects on this topic have fueled my interest. This thesis offers a platform for these ideas to take shape, and importantly, to uncover the underlying reasons driving my fascination through research. I will start my research from the urban system, then expand to other design systems.

By collecting these temporary spaces that would be forgotten, this project emphasizes the cityscape and people that are silent in the process of building and developing modern cities.
Shiqing Chen

embeddings.title: Despierta. To Our Survival.
embeddings.text:
Despierta. To Our Survival.
"Despierta. To our survival" is my personal and emotional story about reconnecting with your inner child. It explores waking up from being kidnapped by family wounds and constant external battles. Let's cheer together for our survival.

This 7-minute art piece can be experienced through a Virtual Reality (VR) headset that immerses you in a multimedia (visual and sound) non-linear radial structure story. Mixing surrealism and South American magic realism, the story connects the subconscious and reality through the memory of family archives and personal objects.

My itp journey and life changing decisions 

The role of thesis in my life

This project at the service for others
César Loayza

embeddings.title: Seed is Power
embeddings.text:
Seed is Power
"Seed is Power: The Voices of Tomatoes" transforms the mundane act of grocery shopping into an immersive journey into the origins and stories of heirloom tomatoes. This innovative retail experience invites customers to not just shop for produce but to engage with the very essence of what they consume. As shoppers reach for a tomato, the rack comes alive with narratives spoken from the perspective of the tomato itself, sharing tales of its heritage, the soil it sprouted from, and the hands that nurtured it. This project seeks to bridge the gap between urban consumers and the agricultural roots of their food, highlighting the importance of seed preservation, biodiversity, and the cultural significance embedded in each seed. Through this interactive experience, "Seed is Power" aims to awaken a sense of curiosity and responsibility towards the choices we make in our diets and to foster a deeper appreciation for the diversity and richness of our agricultural heritage. 

Eric Cheng

embeddings.title: There was a thing, originally
embeddings.text:
There was a thing, originally 
This VR immersive experience project showcases the cultural origins and folklore development of China's Northeast region. It delves into the demographic history through the exploration of Shaman culture and the migration during the Chuang Guan Dong period, highlighting the author's concerns over the future trend of population decline in the area. The project focuses on presenting shamanic rituals from Changbai Mountain and exhibits folk artifacts that are central to the Northeastern culture, thereby guiding the audience to reflect on the cultural richness and the dwindling population trend of the Northeast. Through an immersive portrayal of spiritual practices and the daily life influenced by Shamanism and historical migrations, this experience aims to provide a comprehensive understanding of how these elements have crafted the region's identity. Furthermore, it addresses the critical issue of population decline, prompting thoughts on sustainability and cultural preservation. This project serves as an invitation to explore the complex interplay of history, culture, and community that characterizes the Northeast, offering a unique insight into its past, present, and uncertain future.

Dongxu Xie

embeddings.title: Limen
embeddings.text:
Limen
The experience is split into two out of consideration for keeping the more passive, immersive storytelling aspect intact and self-contained while keeping the more active, functional social platform distinctly independent. Both are indispensable to the overall experience. The first catalyzes you to enter that inward headspace for processing your emotions while the second urges you to look outward and discover a community made up of those who are empathic towards your predicament. 

Part I takes the user on an introspective journey across a poetic rendition of the author’s emotional landscape, traversing through feelings of lost, despair, growth, rebirth and belonging associated with leaving behind his past identity as an architect and venturing into the unknown as a UX designer with all the doubts and questions that haunt him and but also the friends he made along the way. 

Part II morphs from abstraction to reality by presenting an application platform for users to connect with others of similar experience, weaving individual inner reflection with a peer-to-peer support community. The app offers a space for users to share their emotions and most pressing questions with mentors that have walked their paths as well as those on the road. 

The app experience echoes the 4 stages of liminality in the VR experience by repeating questions presented in the game world in a linear pattern inside the app, alternating between topics daily.

Peter Zhang

embeddings.title: Link
embeddings.text:
Link
This project is a VR experience for players to explore three faces of one human being with the theme of “connection”. There are three characters and three places, and these places reflect the faces that human has. The first, a dark pond, symbolizes the deep inner mind, where thoughts swirl unseen and the players are required to balance there. The second, a forest with many paths, represents the outer world, full of possibilities. The third, a bustling café, mirrors the social sphere, filled with the chatter of others and they can distract you(The possibility of using MetaHuman for other players to participate in this space is open). Each place tells its own story, weaving together the complexities of human emotion and interaction. Players would be immersed in those stories by the voices, visuals, and the mysterious atmosphere in the virtual spaces, following and making the sequence of the story by the clues which are unusual phenomena or unfamiliar sounds. As they choose which way to head, they create different stories, and as they get closer to the other spaces, they can sense through sound or visual cues .…..
Hyungin Choi

embeddings.title: Dolĉa Morto: An Experimental Fashion Line Exploring Digital Design & Virtual Production Campaign
embeddings.text:
Dolĉa Morto: An Experimental Fashion Line Exploring Digital Design & Virtual Production Campaign
Dolca Morto represents an innovative experiment at the intersection of technology and fashion, pioneering the integration of advanced digital design and virtual production methodologies into the conventional workflows of the fashion industry. At its core, the project leverages cutting-edge tools such as Clo3D and Marvelous Design for digital clothing creation, alongside Unreal Engine and LED Wall technologies for immersive visual campaigns production.

By bridging the gap between digital innovation and fashion design, Dolca Morto seeks to set a precedent for how the industry can evolve to meet the demands of the modern digital era. Ultimately, Dolca Morto aims to democratize creative freedom and operational agility, encouraging a more inclusive and innovative future for fashion industry professionals. This experiment stands as a beacon for the potential of digital tools to redefine the boundaries of fashion design and creative technology.

With the new design-production pipeline where pattern making, creative marketing and brand campaigns are empowered by these digital technologies, Dolca Morto as a fashion line, incorporates world building and speculative design as design methodologies. It portrays the look of fashion and the virtual world of the postmodern world where humans create a religion of death and life cycle because of the advance of technology.

Haoquan Wang

embeddings.title: Visible Somatic Self
embeddings.text:
Visible Somatic Self 
The Internet has profoundly transformed our lives, shaping our interactions and influencing our core beliefs. Initially, it was the gateway to boundless knowledge, the Internet has, over the past three decades, evolved to impact our emotional selves with a vocabulary that describes the negative impact on our somatic self: trolls, FOMO, On Blast, and the social media’s negative impact on our sense of self. Furthermore, technological advancements in the Internet and our ability to connect 24/7 have altered the very fabric of human connection. This plays out in our families, friendships and at work. It has created great wealth, facilitates our creatively, and many new businesses 

In light of this multifaceted transformation, this thesis seeks to delve into the dynamics of authentic human connection amidst our digital age. Specifically, it aims to explore how leveraging technology can serve as a catalyst for fostering genuine connections by encouraging individuals to reveal their inner selves, thereby sparking meaningful conversations.

Karen Gordon

embeddings.title: low-tec-futurism
embeddings.text:
low-tec-futurism
Imagine we're 1000 years in the future. After consumerism collapsed, people inhabited various planets, connected by orbital transports. Traveling to even the nearest star is prohibitively expensive, leading to each star developing its own unique culture, rituals, and non-digital technologies due to its isolation. From time to time, earth descendants claim indigeneity over these planets and arrange egalitarian societies in which spirituality is quintessential to every aspect of life. This project aims to imagine individual living space and lifestyle in the described scene. 
Haonan Qi

embeddings.title: RIMEDO
embeddings.text:
RIMEDO
RIMEDO is a project to explore how comparative financial analysis among peers can enhance personal financial understanding. Users will be able to respond to questions that delve into various aspects of financial management, such as investment choices, expenditure habits, and income levels. This comparative insight could be invaluable for users to make informed decisions about their personal finances, as it provides a real-world benchmark rather than relying solely on generalized advice.
Bosung Kim

embeddings.title: Playces
embeddings.text:
Playces
How do we bring ourselves into digital places? And how might experiencing a digital place–itself potentially an echo or simulacrum of a physical place–open up new avenues for expression or ways of understanding the design and intent behind our surroundings? Playces is a collection of works that explore these questions while celebrating the level design of first-person shooter video games from the late ‘90s and early 2000s, an era when graphical demands and tooling were aligned such that small teams and even lone individuals regularly made levels or “maps” for games that reached millions of players. Combining sculptural, digital, and historically-grounded audio pieces, the Playces collection also proposes alternative methods for featuring video games in gallery settings; inspired by works from artists including Aram Bartholl and Cory Arcangel, one of the collection's goals is to frame the maps-as-subject in ways that resist purely nostalgic responses and invite non-players to form new attachments to the medium of games.
Mathew Olson

embeddings.title: The Green Tablet
embeddings.text:
The Green Tablet
The Green Tablet presents a collection of objects grown from research into the assemblages around lithium. As light as lithium is, its tentacles bridge the parallels between our invented technological gadgets and medication for our biological bodies in more than metaphors but the literal use of lithium in both batteries, “nerve tonic” for bodily exhaustion and medication for bipolar disorder. The project finds connections deep in the history of how our near religious belief in technology's power to cure societal problems came to be. It revives antique objects that were the products of make-believes. From quack medical devices that uses batteries to heal all diseases, to medical trade cards that ….tbc
Cindy Hu

embeddings.title: Bread Winner
embeddings.text:
Bread Winner
Bread Winner is an idle clicker game that reaps all clicks from the player’s clicks across the browser, whether it be while checking email, filling out a survey, or playing another game. Clicks are used to bake bread, buy power-ups, and boost the rate of production. Through playful and unserious gameplay, Bread Winner aims to explore our compulsion to be productive, highlighting both its absurdity and its addictiveness. By gamifying the smallest unit of digital labor-- the click-- even the most negligible task transforms into an act of production. In a world where laptops, mobile devices, and the internet have made it impossible to escape our work, this game asks us to lean into our compulsive tendencies in order to unravel them.
Isabel Lee

embeddings.title: Magical☆Rhythmie
embeddings.text:
Magical☆Rhythmie
Magical☆Rhythmie is a 2D rhythm JRPG that explores personal growth and the psychology of fame. The development team comprises Kitty Guo, Irene Li, and Sarah Feng. The players will take the role of a high school girl who accidentally obtains the ability to transform into a magical girl, going on an adventure of fighting enemies and protecting the city. In this game, battles are presented in a rhythm game format. Besides battling enemies, players must go through daily events as a high school student. Currently, the team is developing the prototype with RPG systems, including the stats system, skill system, world map, and daily events.
Kitty Guo

embeddings.title: Purrify
embeddings.text:
Purrify
Purrify doesn't just hold your favorite plants; it's also your personal air quality sentinel. Upon detecting compromised air quality, it signals users to open a window or activate an air purifier. It is specifically designed for households with dust-sensitive pets.

Shauna Wu

embeddings.title: HexaVenture
embeddings.text:
HexaVenture
HexaVenture is an innovative project that aims to reduce energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions by combining sustainable design and aerodynamic principles. Its main objective is to provide an alternative to traditional air conditioning systems in environments with moderate temperatures. At its core, HexaVenture seeks to address a critical question: 'How can sustainable design and aerodynamic principles be harnessed to reduce energy consumption and greenhouse gas emissions?' This initiative unveils novel design strategies that leverage the properties of sustainable materials and aerodynamic concepts to bolster natural air circulation, curtailing the necessity for energy-intensive cooling approaches.


Driven by a profound concern for the environment and the imperative to slash greenhouse gas emissions, HexaVenture aspires to decrease its energy footprint significantly in conditions not characterized by extreme temperatures. The project focuses on developing new design strategies that leverage the properties of sustainable materials and aerodynamic concepts to create highly effective passive cooling systems.


HexaVenture is tailored to resonate with a broad spectrum of individuals, ranging from designers and architects focusing on sustainable materials to urban planners in metropolitan areas and inhabitants of developing countries confronting intense heat. By emphasizing utilizing locally sourced, sustainable materials, HexaVenture introduces autonomous passive indoor ventilation systems that are both economically viable and widely accessible. This initiative offers a practical remedy to the challenges presented by urban heat islands and limited cooling technology access. It acts as a beacon of innovation for sustainable design and environmental art.
Chumou Zhang

embeddings.title: Body of Work
embeddings.text:
Body of Work
"Body of Work" is a series of sculptures that depict different body parts of the artist that come together to make a self-portrait. These sculptures explore themes of anxiety, femininity, and play and are manifestations of the artist trying to re-connect with her body. The series invites the viewer to engage with the embodiment of the artist and prompts a curated body scan meditation. Spoiler alert: our relationships with our bodies are constant work.
Priyanka Makin

embeddings.title: Bio Material Research
embeddings.text:
Bio Material Research
We’re living the plastic age. Since the plastic invented, it’s been one of the important materials in our life from industry to daily life. It’s light weight, cost efficient and easy to transform but also easily disposable. Plastic products are abandoned on soil and ocean and pollutes our planet, also the microplastics which made from the plastics cause multiple pollution problems and threatening the health. 

One way to reduce the plastic pollution is well disposing the material, which also intrigues people to think plastic is less valuable also might mislead to create more plastic waste. Recycling the plastic is other way to reduce the plastic pollution however considering how much energy and money spend for the recycling process, it is questionable and think about if there’s better and fundamental solution.

Bio based plastic is one of the solutions for the plastic waste and pollutions. Among those, agar agar bio plastic is one of the interesting material. The agar agar comes from the red algae, Gelidium amansii. The material is soluble in water and when it added with glycerin and following some instruction, it becomes bio based plastic. The agar agar bioplastic can be shaped as casting, dried as a flatten sheet and carved or melted as clay does. It is also remelted in 85 celsius degree and become liquify and technically it is reusable endlessly. 
Nakyung Youn

embeddings.title: AxAR: An Augmented Reality Guitar Learning tool
embeddings.text:
AxAR: An Augmented Reality Guitar Learning tool
An Augmented Reality application for independently learning songs on the guitar. The scope of this project focuses on providing the user with real-time guidance and feedback while playing the instrument, using a passthrough headset. Its goal is to provide a more intuitive and visual approach to music learning compared to past methods which rely on shifting between different points of view between instrument and information.
Orpheas Kofinakos

embeddings.title: What she carried
embeddings.text:
What she carried
This project is a study on generational trauma passed down by witnesses of the Partition. Ordinary objects carried across the border serve as metaphors for the trauma and grief passed down, often unspoken for decades.

The Partition of 1947 was an event that split the subcontinent into three countries: India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh, following colonization. To avoid religious violence, a mass migration took place, resulting in the largest displacement of people in history. While the statistics show us the scale of the event, my focus is on the often unseen aspects: the things they carried and the stories tied to them, threads connecting them to what used to be home.
Aliza Habib

embeddings.title: PowerUp Fitness - AI powered workout App
embeddings.text:
PowerUp Fitness - AI powered workout App
My thesis is an innovative web and mobile application designed to enhance the fitness experience by integrating a comprehensive platform that allows users to locate workout venues and fitness-related stores closest to their location utilizing Augmented Reality for an immersive and intuitive search experience, the project also uses AI-powered fitness training plans, catering to the personalized needs of each user, lastly, the platform provides real time user chat community that fosters a collaborative environment where users can connect, form groups, and engage in real-time workout sessions together. The tech stack for the project includes Next.js for web development, Tailwind CSS for responsive design, Prisma as an efficient database management, Firebase for real-time data handling and authentication, Google Maps API for geolocation services, ChatGPT API for intelligent chatbot interactions. Ultimately, I look forward to building a seamless, user-friendly experience that encourages active lifestyles.
Becky Hsu

embeddings.title: TacTag- Tactile Feedback Prototype Toolkit
embeddings.text:
TacTag- Tactile Feedback Prototype Toolkit
My thesis project introduces a tactile feedback prototype toolkit designed for tactile interface designers at the early stages of product and interface development. This wearable device, paired with a web application, allows designers to experiment with a spectrum of tactile interactions like squeezing and rubbing via modular hardware components. The toolkit facilitates a deeper understanding of user perception and interaction with tactile feedback, contributing to a foundation for future tactile-based communication interfaces.
Lang Qin

embeddings.title: Sense making
embeddings.text:
Sense making
“We are always embodied, whether that is in the form of clothes, the built environment or through technology…” 
Sarah Mok

embeddings.title: My Dear Friend
embeddings.text:
My Dear Friend
Have you wished for a friendship that will last forever? In every stage of my life, I have close friends that belong to the specific period of time. When it is time for separation, we go to different places for our own pursuit. While people keep moving and seeking new opportunities, we keep losing and building friendship. This is a live performance with one dancer and another ‘virtual dancer’ that tells a story about how modern friendship endures over time.
Yuke Ding
